<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="chp3sec3" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Relatively Prime Diagonal Grid</title>

  <p> </p>
  
  <definition xml:id="definition-relatively_prime_diagonal_grid">
    <title>The Relatively Prime Diagonal Grid</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            If integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> are relatively prime and greater than 1, then the <term>relatively prime diagonal grid</term> is the <m>m</m> by <m>n</m> grid of least residues modulo <m>mn</m> written sequentially diagonally down and to the right, where you loop upon hitting and edge.  In symbols, the least residue <m>k\in\{0,1,\ldots,mn-1\}</m> will be placed in row <m>i\equiv k\pmod m</m> and column <m>j\equiv k\pmod n</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>For example, the relatively prime diagonal grid for <m>m=2</m> and <m>n=3</m> is:</p>

  <tabular bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
  <row bottom="minor">
    <cell right="minor">0</cell>
    <cell>4</cell>
    <cell>2</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell right="minor"
    >3</cell>
    <cell>1</cell>
    <cell>5</cell>
  </row>
</tabular>

<p>The relatively prime diagonal grid for <m>m=6</m> and <m>n=7</m> is:</p>

<tabular halign="center" top="minor" left="minor" bottom="minor" right="minor">
    <row bottom="minor">
        <cell right="minor">0</cell>
        <cell right="minor">36</cell>
        <cell right="minor">30</cell>
        <cell right="minor">24</cell>
        <cell right="minor">18</cell>
        <cell right="minor">12</cell>
        <cell right="minor">6</cell>
    </row>
    <row bottom="minor">
        <cell right="minor">7</cell>
        <cell right="minor">1</cell>
        <cell right="minor">37</cell>
        <cell right="minor">31</cell>
        <cell right="minor">25</cell>
        <cell right="minor">19</cell>
        <cell right="minor">13</cell>
    </row>
    <row bottom="minor">
        <cell right="minor">14</cell>
        <cell right="minor">8</cell>
        <cell right="minor">2</cell>
        <cell right="minor">38</cell>
        <cell right="minor">32</cell>
        <cell right="minor">26</cell>
        <cell right="minor">20</cell>
    </row>
    <row bottom="minor">
        <cell right="minor">21</cell>
        <cell right="minor">15</cell>
        <cell right="minor">9</cell>
        <cell right="minor">3</cell>
        <cell right="minor">39</cell>
        <cell right="minor">33</cell>
        <cell right="minor">27</cell>
    </row>
    <row bottom="minor">
        <cell right="minor">28</cell>
        <cell right="minor">22</cell>
        <cell right="minor">16</cell>
        <cell right="minor">10</cell>
        <cell right="minor">4</cell>
        <cell right="minor">40</cell>
        <cell right="minor">34</cell>
    </row>
    <row bottom="minor">
        <cell right="minor">35</cell>
        <cell right="minor">29</cell>
        <cell right="minor">23</cell>
        <cell right="minor">17</cell>
        <cell right="minor">11</cell>
        <cell right="minor">5</cell>
        <cell right="minor">41</cell>
    </row>
</tabular>

    <activity>
		<title>Create the Relatively Prime Diagonal Grid</title>
		<p>
			Create the relatively prime diagonal grid for <m>m=4</m> and <m>n=5</m>.  What patterns do you see? Can you find a pattern in the columns and rows?
		</p>

    <p>
			Try to create a similar grid for <m>m=3</m> and <m>n=6</m>.  What goes wrong?  Why do you think the condition of relatively prime is necessary?  
		</p>
  </activity>


 <proposition xml:id="proposition-relatively_prime_diagonal_grid_is_filled">
  <title>The relatively prime diagonal grid is filled</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>m,n\in \Z</m> are integers greater than 1 and <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> are relatively prime, each spot in the relatively prime diagonal grid  is filled with precisely one least residue modulo <m>mn</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof.  Suppose some spot in the grid is not filled.  What does that mean?  Why is that a problem?  Next suppose some spot in the grid is filled with more than one least residue modulo <m>mn</m>.  What does that mean?  Why is that a problem?  You may find  <xref ref="definition-relatively_prime_diagonal_grid"/>, <xref ref="definition-least_residue"/>, and <xref ref="proposition-congruence_and_least_residue"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition> 

 <proposition xml:id="proposition-columns_and_rows_of_relatively_prime_diagonal_grid">
  <title>The columns and rows of the relatively prime diagonal grid</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>m,n\in \Z</m> are integers greater than 1 and <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> are relatively prime, then the elements of a column are all congruent modulo <m>n</m> and the elements of a row are all congruent modulo <m>m</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof.  Let <m>c</m> be an element in a column.  Why are all the elements in that column congruent to <m>c</m> modulo <m>n</m>?  Next let <m>r</m> be an element in a row.  Why are all the elements in that row congruent to <m>r</m> modulo <m>m</m>?  You may find  <xref ref="definition-relatively_prime_diagonal_grid"/>, <xref ref="definition-least_residue"/>, and <xref ref="proposition-congruence_and_least_residue"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition> 



 
</section>